tuations were resolved (to gauge the severity and manageability of the issue).\nGathering this additional data will allow us to confirm whether Candidate\u202fB\u2019s interpersonal drawbacks are manageable or if another candidate might outweigh them.\nMETADATA_JSON:\n{\"agent\": \"agent_2\", \"vote\": \"Candidate B\"}", "thoughts": "We have gathered additional info from agents 1 and 3, which essentially repeats that there is no detailed info beyond what we already have. Now we need to produce our public contribution: summarize overall assessment, maybe ask further clarifying questions, and vote.\n\nWe have all the info now: Candidate A: strengths (anticipates danger, complex connections, spatial vision, leadership) but weaknesses (show-off, not open to new ideas, unorganized, not good at taking criticism). No explicit reliability.\n\nCandidate B: strengths (100% reliable, calm in crisis, weather assessment, computer skills) weaknesses (grumpy, uncooperative, nasty remarks, pretentious, wrong tone). No documented impact.\n\nCandidate C: strengths (quick correct decisions, handles stress, positive crew atmosphere, conscientious, understands complicated technology) weaknesses (difficulty communicating ideas, egocentric, not willing to further education). No specific technical details.\n\nCandidate D: strengths (responsibility, problem solving, concentration, responds to unexpected events) weaknesses (arrogant, know-it-all, hot temper, weak leadership, moody, loner). No communication examples.\n\nNow we need to evaluate holistically for long-distance pilot. The key criteria: reliability, technical competence, calm under pressure, decision-making, teamwork, professional development.\n\nReliability: B is 100% reliable. D takes responsibility seriously (maybe reliable). A unorganized, no reliability. C unknown.\n\nTechnical competence: B (weather, computer). A (spatial vision, complex connections). D (problem solving). C (understands complicated technology). But B seems m